WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:08.167
And what they do, of course, is they use deep learning as you might have guessed to do that.

00:08.187 --> 00:16.745
So they will have a model that for a particular start and end goal will give them a probability distribution across candidates.

00:16.845 --> 00:21.955
Now, everything that's black here also has probability mass, but it's just so small you can't see.

00:21.935 --> 00:30.884
And these blue ones are the lighter blue, the more probable this model thinks that this is going to be an in-between state.

00:31.825 --> 00:39.593
Now the tree search can now limit itself effectively to only the ones here with the highest probability, right?

00:39.894 --> 00:49.984
So we select the ones with the highest probability and we'll only search plans that have these as the first possible subdivisions.

00:49.964 --> 00:52.406
Again, we're searching over plans.

00:52.566 --> 00:57.851
So we're searching over ways to subdivide the problem into smaller problems.

00:57.991 --> 00:59.132
That is our search space.

00:59.793 --> 01:06.999
So once we've decided on one of them, let's say here the yellow one, again, we have to evaluate that model for each of the sub problems.

01:07.019 --> 01:09.402
And this, this is kind of a step that's missing here.

01:09.422 --> 01:19.971
So in between here, there would be a model evaluation that would again tell you which of these in between states were probable subdivision candidates.

01:19.951 --> 01:24.200
and then you would select again one of those in that particular search branch.

01:24.541 --> 01:34.382
And in a different search branch, you're searching over these things, in a different search branch you would select a different one and see is this possibly a better way to subdivide the problem.

